<TEXT>
the agriculture department is launching a 
quackdown on duck growers who call their birds long island 
ducklings even when theyre raised as far away as wisconsin or 
pennsylvania 
the action comes after a fivemonth investigation into alleged 
mislabeling of ducks it was prompted by a complaint from rep 
george hochbrueckner dny whose eastern long island district 
includes some of the regions last duck farms 
were not looking for anything other than fairness doug 
corwin a fourthgeneration duck farmer said tuesday from 
aquebogue ny 
im objecting to the bogus address which gives the 
restaurateur or the consumer the misconception hes getting a long 
island product which in fact he isnt 
on march 21 the agriculture department sent letters to five 
duck processors telling them it found their labels false or 
misleading said jim greene a spokesman for the departments food 
safety and inspection service 
department investigators doing what greene called basic gumshoe 
work found that some duck farmers only connection to long island 
was a post office box yet their products carried such labels as 
pride of long islands south shore or genuine long island 
distributed duckling 
the issue is simply that in order for it to be labeled long 
island duck or duckling the animal has to have been raised or 
slaughtered on long island greene said 
he identified the five as concord farms inc of concord nc 
joe jurgielewicz amp sons ltd of shartlesville pa culver corp of 
middlebury ind maple leaf farms inc of milford ind and maple 
leaf duck farm inc of franksville wis 
the five have 60 days to respond to the agriculture department 
then if the ruling becomes final and they continue to put long 
island labels on their ducks the agriculture inspector at the 
plant wont let the birds off the premises greene said 
barbara bender marketing director for concord farms said 
long island duck is merely a marketing phrase 
its not a breed its a place she said 
even when they sell restaurants north carolina duck the 
restaurants still list it on the menu as long island duckling she 
added 
but on long island corwin said the mislabeling has cut into his 
market particularly in places like florida and texas 
our problem comes in markets where we are not wellknown he 
said say if we were asked for a bid we could not outbid a plant 
in the midwest that had lower costs and yet the bids would specify 
genuine long island products 
those outofstate farmers also are trading on long islands 
reputation for raising leaner meatier ducks said joe gergela of 
the long island farm bureau 
long island produces about 2 million ducks a year down from 
about 5 million to 6 million 30 years ago corwin said production 
has declined steadily over the years as land development high 
taxes and escalating utility costs squeezed out farmers 
at one time long island had nearly 100 duck farms now there 
are about a halfdozen 
corwin whose greatgrandfather began raising ducks in 1908 
produces about half the islands annual total 
id like to keep growing ducks out here for a few 
generations he said 
</TEXT>
