<TEXT>
in some agriculture department circles the 
buzz words these days are africanized honeybees 
not killer bees mind you thats all beeswax dreamed up by 
hollywood and the news media the usda has a new backgrounder 
report to straighten things out 
africanized honeybees from mexico are expected to arrive in 
texas sometime during 199192 by natural spread although some 
swarms may arrive sooner the report said 
the early arrivals could be occasional swarms coming from south 
and central america aboard ships those are a concern but they 
are not major threats to americans or the us beekeeping 
industry it said 
some domestic beekeepers are fearful that the spread of 
africanized bees could jeopardize the us industry which includes 
commercial crop pollination services as well as honey production 
it has been a long trail for the africanized honeybees 
descendants of 26 african swarms imported by researchers in brazil 
in 1956 who were trying to develop more productive models than the 
traditional european honeybee 
as the africanized swarms multiplied and spread into neighboring 
south american countries they also marched north across the 
continent gaining an evil reputation by the early 1980s they were 
in panama and it was obvious their march would take them into 
mexico and into the united states 
researchers named them africanized honeybees the report 
said however as a result of widely publicized stinging 
incidents the name killer bee was picked up by the movie 
industry and the media to describe the africanized honeybee 
the report said everyday risks such as auto accidents pose a 
much greater risk statistically than death from beestings 
according to routes indicated by the report the bees are 
expected to make their us entry near the southernmost tip of 
texas 
the africanized bee is more dangerous than its larger european 
cousin which incidentally was introduced into north america by 
european settlers or maybe it isnt it depends how many are 
involved 
unlike the docile european honeybees common in the united 
states the africanized honeybee quickly defends its hive and will 
pursue intruders longer distances the report said the venom 
from one africanized honeybee sting is no more potent than the 
venom of a single european honeybee sting 
one of the widely reported characteristics of the africanized 
bees is their defensive behavior in which hundreds or thousands 
quickly and aggressively respond to an intruder each carrying a 
potential sting to the victim 
even though mass stinging attacks are terrifying and could be 
lifethreatening they are not common the report said the 
best defense for avoiding stings from all stinging insects not 
just honeybees is common sense 
the report added if you find yourself near large numbers of 
honeybees calmly and quickly move away from the area 
</TEXT>
