a government report says northern areas of the 
great plains still suffer from lack of moisture for crops and 
pastures but farther south the story was too much rain 
rain improved winter wheat condition in portions of the 
central great plains during the week of march 26april 1 the 
joint agricultural weather facility reported tuesday crop 
condition was mostly good in colorado and kansas nebraskas winter 
wheat was fair to good 
in the southern plains too much moisture caused some yellowing 
of the wheat crop and hampered fertilizer application the crop 
condition was said to be good to fair in oklahoma and missouri 
rain improved winter wheat in northern texas but excess moisture 
was a problem in some areas 
winter wheat was mostly good in the corn belt and good to fair 
in the southeast the report said powdery mildew was a 
continuing problem in georgia 
in the west lack of moisture put stress on winter wheat in the 
columbia basin of oregon the report said washingtons wheat was 
in goodtofair shape although russian wheat aphids were a problem 
in the eastern part of the state 
pastures and livestock were reported in goodtofair condition 
in the mississippi delta region and in the east ranges in most of 
the west needed rain but livestock was said to be in mostly 
good condition 
the facility is operated by the agriculture and commerce 
departments weekly reports cover crop conditions but do not 
include production forecasts 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
japan has moved ahead of the united states as 
the worlds largest pork importer says an agriculture department 
report 
the us market share of world pork imports dropped to 28 
percent in 1988 from 34 percent in 1985 said the report by the 
departments foreign agricultural service meanwhile japans 
import share rose to 28 percent from 18 percent 
for 1989 through 1990 the united states market share is 
forecast to fall then remain at 25 percent while japans share is 
forecast to rise to 31 percent the report said 
the rise in japans pork imports was attributed to domestic 
pressure calling for greater availability and lower prices for 
meat also the report cited the governments move to reduce import 
levies 
