two steel companies paid employees expenses 
to travel here against their unions wishes to rally against a 
cleanair bill that the industry opposes according to company and 
union officials 
the united steelworkers of america which supports the bill 
used memos and telephone calls to try to hold down the size of 
tuesdays demonstration members of a steelworkers local in 
pennsylvania decided not to come because the union leadership 
advised against it 
still the demonstration on the capitol steps was attended by 
about 150 workers many from usx corps steelmaking plants in 
gary ind and fairless hills pa and the companys ore facility 
at mountain iron minn 
usx paid the expenses of its workers who attended said 
spokesman ernie glenn 
ltv corp also sponsored some of its steelworkers from cleveland 
and warren ohio so they could come according to spokesman chuck 
hess 
we look at this as sponsoring a rally for employees who have 
expressed concern about this legislation and what it might mean for 
them and their families glenn said im not going to comment 
on what the international the union says or does 
when he heard about the rally at the end of last week 
steelworkers president lynn williams sent a memorandum to union 
directors nationwide 
the steel companies are attempting to take advantage of our 
basic steel local unions by planning an allexpenses companypaid 
rally in washington the memo said it is not a rally which the 
united steelworkers of america supports the steel companies are 
not themselves opposing the act but are using our members to front 
for them 
charlie grese president of the union local at the usx plant in 
clairton pa said in a telephone interview that he changed his 
mind about attending after speaking to williams and other union 
officials on the phone 
theres no question we were about ready to come down grese 
said i told the company i would have to take this past the 
international union and would not come down without authorization 
from the international president 
grese said he decided not to go after being told by the unions 
chief lobbyist that the rally would do little good because it was 
too late to change any minds the senate approved the bill 
8911 tuesday night 
demonstrators at the rally opposed a requirement in the bill 
that people living near steel plant coke ovens could not be exposed 
to a cancer risk of more than one in 10000 over 70 years 
the demonstrators expressed concern that such a guideline was 
unrealistic and could force the mandatory shutdown of dozens of 
coke ovens coke which comes from coal is a raw material of 
steel coke ovens can emit benzene a carcinogen 
