<TEXT>
education secretary lauro cavazos says hes 
convinced that some house democrats are playing politics with the 
presidents bill to improve us schools 
the bottom line is simple some people just have a difficult 
time giving the president any credit for the efforts and leadership 
he has taken in improving and restructuring our nations schools 
said cavazos 
he chastised the house education and labor committee for not 
advancing the administrations 15 billion bill to upgrade 
education an alternative offered by chairman augustus hawkins 
dcalif is a ploy to sidetrack the presidents bill cavazos 
said 
i am disappointed that the administration legislation has 
been treated in a highly partisan fashion cavazos told the 
subcommittee on elementary secondary and vocational education 
it is not a partisan bill it is an education reform bill 
however many education leaders testified in favor of hawkins 
bill including keith geiger president of the national education 
association franklin smith of the council of the great city 
schools and gordon ambach director of the council of chief state 
school officers 
the subcommittee however became embroiled in a partisan war of 
words 
rep william f goodling rpa who introduced the 
administrations bill with 98 cosponsors complained that the 
democrats bill was 177 pages thrown together in two weeks with 
not much thought and very few details on how various sections 
would be implemented 
