<TEXT>
the bush administration facing growing 
congressional opposition to the costly b2 stealth bomber is 
weighing plans to scale back production of the aircraft says air 
force secretary donald rice 
in his first public comments on the pentagons review of major 
weapons systems rice said the defense department is examining 
other options to the current plan to buy 132 bombers at a cost of 
more than 70 billion 
we think there are some alternate profiles with some very 
modest effect on the total cost of the program rice told the 
senate appropriations subcommittee on defense tuesday 
major concerns in the pentagon center on the possibility that 
purchasing less than the full fleet will force up the cost of a 
single radarevading bomber now estimated at about 530 million 
rice said pending legislation that would stop production at the 
15 bombers currently being built would mean a total program cost of 
33 billion to 34 billion based on those numbers a single plane 
would cost more than 2 billion he noted 
defense secretary dick cheney has been reviewing the 
alternatives rice said the air force has scheduled another 
briefing for the pentagon chief on the b2 on thursday 
president bushs 307 billion defense budget for fiscal 1991 
which begins oct 1 calls for 55 billion for the stealth bomber 
program including the purchase of five planes and other expenses 
but in the mid1990s the administration is projecting purchases 
of 10 planes and later 24 in a single year with annual costs of 
nearly 10 billion 
rice said the most efficient production rate for the planes 
manufacturer northrop corp is 29 planes a year but the air 
force secretary conceded that it will be difficult to persuade 
congress to spend almost 10 billion a year on a single weapons 
program 
pressed for the options the pentagon is weighing rice said i 
cant give numbers except to say several billion dollars a year 
less than peak funding level of close to 10 billion 
it would inevitably get up to a lower production rate on the 
order of twothirds perhaps threefourths what had been peak 
rate rice said in reference to the 29 bombers a year 
democrats and republicans on the panel made it clear that the 
b2 program for which the government has invested more than 23 
billion faces an uphill fight in congress 
sen robert kasten rwis a proponent of the stealth bomber 
questioned rice on the alternatives to the full fleet of 132 
bombers a total that many lawmakers say is unlikely 
im trying to help you guys with this weapons system kasten 
said today its hard to help 
