<TEXT>
if americans are to continue paying less for 
food than anyone else in the world target prices set by the 
government for crops must be tied to production costs say five 
senators working on the pricesupport section of the 1990 farm bill 
us consumers today spend just 104 percent of their 
disposable income on food the lowest level in history and less 
than consumers in any other country sen robert kerrey dneb 
said tuesday 
but the producers share of each dollar spent on food has 
dropped to an alltime low he said at a news conference called 
to outline legislation expected to be the basis of the target price 
and income support section of the senate farm bill 
meanwhile tuesday a house subcommittee approved a dairy program 
for the house version of the massive legislation that congress 
designs every five years to set agriculture policy 
under the house dairy program the government would buy up to 7 
billion pounds of milk products at 1060 per hundred pounds if 
they cant be sold on the open market farmers who produce more 
than their share of the governments limit would get a sharply 
lower amount 
the key to the legislation is reducing butter production which 
because of low consumer demand is ending up in government 
warehouses 
the senate has not yet acted on dairy 
kerrey was joined by sens james exon dneb tom daschle 
dsd tom harkin diowa and kent conrad dnd to push for 
raising target prices on socalled program crops wheat corn 
cotton soybeans and rice 
the legislation would cost about 12 billion annually said 
kerrey who has led the fight against a bush administration 
proposal designed to lower target prices 
the government sets target prices to assure farmers a certain 
income if the market price does not reach the target price the 
government pays the farmer the difference 
the senators said their plan would protect family farms which 
an aide to daschle mark ulvensaid was important as a guard 
against higher supermarket prices if agricultural production were 
in the hands of just a few corporate farms food prices would also 
be under their control he said 
kerrey said the plans aim is not to heavily subsidize farmers 
he said the democrats are interested in seeing farmers produce for 
the market not government subsidies 
but he said recovery is fragile and the government should 
assure that farmers production costs are covered 
provisions in the proposed legislation include 
tying target prices to increased production costs 
raising loan rates which help determine market prices by more 
than 20 percent next year and setting a floor on the loan rate of 
210 for corn and 275 for wheat 
establishing a normal crop acreage base for each farm that is 
the total of the farms current cropspecific bases plus the 
average acreage planted to soybeans during the last five years 
raising income support levels on oilseeds oats and barley to 
levels comparable with wheat and corn 
</TEXT>
