<TEXT>
in the first survey of its kind homosexual 
members of the staffs of american newspapers say their papers do a 
poor job in the way they treat news about gays or of concern to 
them 
the gay journalists said their papers treat them fairly and give 
them opportunity to advance but rarely call on their insights into 
gay lifestyles in the same way black reporters are asked to help 
guide coverage of black issues 
and some newsrooms harbor a palpable undercurrent of bias a 
summary of the findings concludes one respondent commented that 
her colleagues who make snide homophobic comments and jokes are 
the same people who write those sensitive stories and 
editorials 
the survey was being made public today at the annual meeting of 
the american society of newspaper editors it was undertaken in 
response to outgoing asne president loren ghiglione who asked 
whether antigay discrimination infects todays newsrooms 
when word circulated that the survey was to be undertaken 205 
homosexual members of the staffs of us newspapers volunteered to 
respond threefifths said they were openly gay and twothirds 
signed their questionnaires 
ninetytwo percent said they knew other people on the staff who 
were gay and the majority of them estimated that fewer than 20 
percent of the homosexuals on their papers were openly gay 
many experts estimate that one american in 10 is gay 
why does it matter asked leroy f aarons an executive of 
the oakland calif tribune who coordinated the project he said 
the subject is important because more than ever before editors 
are grappling with a swirl of social and political currents around 
alternative lifestyle issues 
domestic partners legislation gay adoption 
antidiscrimination laws fundamentalist attacks on the gay 
lifestyle morality and public responsibility and of course the 
stillraging aids epidemic have brought onceeasily ignored issues 
into demanding focus he said 
the respondents gave especially low ratings to the way their 
papers treated gay lifestyles community events and politics and 
only slightly better ratings to treatment of violence against gays 
civil rights issues and legislation 
as for terminology nearly a third said they found the term 
homosexual to be prejudiced explaining that it refers narrowly 
to sex whereas the term gay refers to lifestyles or issues 
another report at the meeting looked at what happens to 
newspapers when they are taken over by nonlocal ownership a 
majority of the editors said firms owning multiple newspapers are 
more interested in profits than in the communities they serve and 
that freedom of the press is in more jeopardy when the ownership of 
papers is concentrated in fewer hands 
some editors said that group ownership was likely to enrich a 
local paper because the group brought greater resources to it some 
said group ownership led to homogenization 
editors of 234 newspapers half groupowned and half 
independent took part 
the report noted that 50 years ago there were 1559 
independent locally owned dailies and only 319 under group 
ownership but now there are only 389 independents and 1233 
groupowned papers 
groupowned papers the report said were likely to offer 
better career opportunities more sharing of ideas less pressure 
from advertisers and special interest groups greater overall 
financial resources and access to outside experts to help solve 
problems and train staff 
independent papers on the other hand were likely to offer 
larger newsroom budgets better understanding of the local 
market more flexibility in making decisions greater involvement 
in the community less turnover of key personnel few levels of 
bureaucracy and a tendency to be peculiar 
the asnes annual survey of minority employment on newspapers 
showed that 786 percent of newsroom editors reporters and 
photographers were members of racial minorities a scant increase 
from last years 754 percent 
when the survey started in 1978 blacks hispanics asians and 
american indians constituted 395 percent of the news staffs the 
figure has risen gradually each year 
in these tough economic times perhaps any increase in the 
percentage of people of color should be applauded said ghiglione 
said 
but merv aubespin chairman of the asne minorities committee 
said the slight gain was embarrassing for our industry which 
prides itself on putting the spotlight on the ills of society 
the survey said minorities make up 46 percent of newsroom 
supervisors 8 percent of copy editors 87 percent of reporters 
and 107 percent of photographers 
