gold whose value skyrocketed as it sat on 
the sea bottom for 133 years has lured columbia university into a 
court battle over the wreck of the ss central america 
the trial that opened tuesday originally pitted the 
columbusamerica discovery group a group of 100 investors with 
exclusive rights to search the ocean bottom for the wreck and the 
45 companies who claim ties to the ships original insurers 
but it was complicated by an announcement that columbia was 
entering the fray the ivy league university contends one of its 
researchers provided data used to locate the goldladen wreck that 
is valued at 450 million to 1 billion 
the exact location of the ship which sank in 1857 about 160 
miles off charleston sc is contained in files sealed by us 
district judge richard b kellam 
columbias attorneys maintain a 1984 sonar survey by dr william 
ryan a columbia oceanographer was the basis for the wrecks 
