the us court of appeals says it agrees with 
a lower court that the seven bell operating companies cannot enter 
the longdistance or telephone equipment businesses 
however tuesdays ruling reopens the possibility that the 
socalled baby bells can sell electronic information services to 
homes and offices 
the decision means that us district judge harold greene must 
consider anew whether the bell companies may be allowed to develop 
socalled electronic yellow pages allowing consumers to shop 
and bank among other possibilities via cheap easytouse video 
terminals 
a prototype system in france called minitel already serves 5 
million homes and offices and offers 8000 different services 
the threejudge appeals panel found that greene ruled correctly 
when in his 1987 triennial review of the american telephone 
and telegraph co antitrust settlement he sustained the original 
order barring the seven spinoff companies from competing with their 
onetime parent in the longdistance and telephone manufacturing 
arenas 
but appeals judges abner mikva harry edwards and laurence 
silberman faulted greenes legal reasoning when as part of that 
same review he only partially opened the door for the operating 
companies to expand into computerbased information services 
greene allowed the bell companies to offer computer gateways and 
access menus for databases and services offered by other firms 
but not to generate those services themselves that precluded them 
from pursuing a us version of frances governmentoperated 
minitel system 
kenneth pitt media relations director of bell atlantic 
expressed excitement over the appellate ruling though he conceded 
greene could still rule against the bell companies offering a 
variety of prospective services that include banking home 
shopping news real estate listings and medical monitoring 
