<TEXT>
arthur houghton jr former president of steuben 
glass and onetime chairman of the metropolitan museum of art has 
died at 83 
houghton died tuesday at venice fla hospital after a brief 
illness 
houghton was a greatgrandson of armory houghton who founded 
corning glass works in 1851 he became president of steuben glass 
a corning subsidiary in 1933 and built its worldwide reputation 
during his 40 years in charge 
company legend has it that shortly after he took over steuben 
houghton spent a sunday smashing every piece of glass in a company 
warehouse to show his dissatisfaction with the design 
the companys new designs came to be shown in museums in this 
country and abroad and steuben adopted the slogan from ash can 
to museum in half a century 
houghton was president of the metropolitan from 1964 to 1969 in 
1969 he was became chairman of the museums board and served until 
1972 
he sat on the new york philharmonics board from 1952 to 1965 
and served as chairman from 1958 to 1963 he was also vice chairman 
of a committee to create lincoln center where the philharmonic 
moved in 1962 
houghton is survived by his wife nina a son and two daughters 
by previous marriages funeral arrangements were not immediately 
known 
</TEXT>
