<TEXT>
a drug used to treat genital herpes has been 
found to speed up childrens recovery from chickenpox a university 
of minnesota study says 
acyclovir reduced the number of itchy blisters and shortened by 
a day the normal fiveday course of chickenpox in 50 twin cities 
children who received the drug according to a report in this 
months journal of pediatrics 
acyclovir is a safe and effective treatment for the illness 
which almost every american gets sometime during childhood said 
dr henry balfour the pediatrician who headed the study 
balfour said tuesday that the finding is important because most 
complications develop near the end of a typical fiveday infection 
he said some doctors may delay prescribing acyclovir until 
results of a larger 10city study are released probably later 
this year 
other doctors may limit the use of acyclovir to youngsters 11 
and older who tend to have the most severe cases of chickenpox 
balfour said but he predicted that its use eventually will be 
widespread 
chickenpox is caused by the varicellazoster virus a member of 
the herpes family of viruses so it was natural to try the herpes 
drug against it he said 
about 35 million americans a year develop chickenpox about 
4000 children are hospitalized each year from complications of the 
disease which include skin or ear infections pneumonia and brain 
infections balfour said 
no chickenpox vaccine is licensed for use in the united states 
but vaccines are being tried in other countries he said 
in the study within a day of developing their first chickenpox 
sores 50 youngsters got a syrup containing acyclovir and 52 others 
got one with no medication in it 
the children getting the acyclovir ended up developing an 
average of 336 skin lesions compared with more than 500 lesions 
for those who didnt get it 
healing started within a day after the youngsters got acyclovir 
compared with two days for those who didnt get it 
blood tests a year later indicated that acyclovir didnt 
interfere with the youngsters developing immunity to this virus a 
process that normally prevents a person from having a second case 
of chickenpox 
the study sponsored in part by burroughs wellcome co 
manufacturer of acyclovir was carried out from february through 
june 1987 testing for immunity and analysis took two years 
</TEXT>
