<TEXT>
for more than half of the nations 20000 
hemophiliacs the aids virus is a fixture of daily life just like 
the blood protein supplements that both keep them well and gave 
them the dangerous infection 
like ryan white the indiana teenager whose fight against aids 
bias made him a national symbol most hemophiliacs became infected 
during the early 1980s before anyone knew that the virus was 
spreading silently by means of their medical treatment 
hemophilia is an inherited disorder in which blood fails to clot 
properly to prevent uncontrolled bleeding hemophiliacs need 
infusions of factor viii a bloodclotting protein that their 
bodies lack the substance is refined from the blood of many donors 
the treatment became tainted with hiv the aids virus between 
1978 and 1984 better cleansing techniques eventually made factor 
viii free of hiv but by then thousands of hemophiliacs were 
already infected 
the national hemophilia foundation in new york now estimates 
that about 55 percent of the nations 20000 hemophiliacs carry 
hiv the uncertainty of when or if they will develop aids is a 
simple fact of life for these people 
about 1200 of the 125000 aids victims since the epidemic began 
have been hemophiliacs but those numbers are likely to grow 
perhaps substantially 
this is what scare us the most said alan brownstein 
executive director of the hemophilia foundation all of these 
people were infected at least six years ago as we learn more about 
the incubation period we know we are getting closer and closer to 
a time when even more people with hemophilia will get aids 
to help forestall this the drug azt is now recommended for 
infected hemophiliacs whose blood counts fall below a certain 
level however some doctors say that many outwardly well 
hemophiliacs are reluctant to begin routine treatment with this 
medicine 
in fact despite their high risk hemophiliacs often appear 
reluctant to face up to the possibility that they might die from 
aids brownstein said that in some parts of the country onethird 
of hemophiliacs have not been tested to see if they are infected 
some say this denial is simply another facet of going through 
life with a disease that makes routine chores and pleasures 
hazardous for people with severe hemophilia a fall or a cut can 
cause dangerous bleeding 
there are strong denial elements that exist for many 
hemophiliacs if they didnt have denial skills from early 
childhood they never would have taken the training wheels off 
their bikes said dr richard lipton of long island jewish 
hospital 
dr bruce furie of new england medical center in boston said 
some infected hemophiliacs seem to take comfort from the fact that 
physicians cannot tell them with 100 percent confidence that they 
will get aids 
they are living normal and productive lives he said they 
went through their crisis three or four years ago when they found 
out they were infected most of them are still going along with 
their activities but with the knowledge that they are playing 
russian roulette and dont know when or if the gun will go off 
making factor viii free of hiv was expensive and the cost of 
therapy has increased 10fold since the discovery of aids routine 
treatment of a patient with severe hemophilia can now range from 
50000 to 100000 a year 
</TEXT>
