<TEXT>
a transplant of insulinproducing cells enabled 
a woman with diabetes to go without daily insulin injections for 
more than two weeks say researchers at washington university 
however after that period the womans body began to reject the 
transplant doctors said 
researchers david scharp and paul lacy said tuesday that the 
case was the first time transplanted cells temporarily eliminated 
the need for insulin injections in a patient with juvenileonset 
diabetes researchers previously had only been able to reduce the 
need for insulin they said 
the results were announced in the april issue of the journal 
diabetes 
the 36yearold patient was one of several given a pancreatic 
islet cell transplant during pilot clinical trials at washington 
university school of medicine and barnes hospital in st louis 
islets are pockets of hormoneproducing tissue that release 
insulin 
the transplanted cells injected into the patients liver were 
removed from the islets of two cadaver pancreases 
jay s skyler vice president of the american diabetes 
association and professor of medicine at the university of miami 
said the study was promising but he cautioned that it was only one 
step toward a cure 
we still have a ways to go skyler said now weve got to 
figure out why its only temporary 
skyler noted that researchers have been able to reverse diabetes 
in rodents using this procedure since 1972 but until now had been 
unsuccessful in applying it to humans 
its an exciting step one thats been elusive for a very long 
time skyler said it was almost getting to the point that many 
people were getting totally discouraged that the corner would ever 
be turned 
scharp also warned that it might be years before islet cell 
transplantation became a routine treatment for diabetics 
we are immensely pleased that the grafted tissue was able to 
satisfy all of the patients insulin requirements before it was 
rejected said scharp who conducted the transplant our first 
trials in 1985 were designed to determine that islet transplants 
were safe in this study our primary goal was to determine if we 
could isolate purify and transplant enough islets to bring a 
patient completely off of insulin 
within 10 days of the transplant the patient no longer required 
daily insulin injections according to hourly bloodsugar tests 
she remained independent of insulin until the 25th day when 
evidence of tissue rejection appeared and she began to require 
gradually increasing amounts of supplemental insulin 
the case shows that islet transplantation is a feasible 
approach to controlling insulindependent diabetes and clearly 
establishes the need to move on to larger clinical trials said 
lacy a pathologist at washington university who devised many of 
the techniques used to isolate and purify human islet cells 
lacy said the researchers hope to draw on previous research to 
find ways to combat rejection of the cells 
</TEXT>
