a decision will be found that will be satisfactory to both 
sides said laptev the progressive editor of izvestia 
lithuanian legislator egidijus bickauskas said of the meeting 
we are very very encouraged 
if there are people who at least want to listen to us its 
very good bickauskas said 
the clash of wills over lithuanian independence has included an 
order from gorbachev for lithuanians to relinquish all weapons the 
arrest by soviet troops of some lithuanian deserters the takeover 
of several vilnius buildings by soviet soldiers movements of army 
reinforcements and a sharp war of words 
soviet foreign minister eduard a shevardnadze was in washington 
for talks with president bush and secretary of state james a baker 
iii and said the kremlin intended to hold honest dialogue with 
the lithuanians 
an expected meeting this morning with soviet interior minister 
vadim bakatin did not occur according to a spokeswoman for the 
lithuanian office in moscow she was unable to say if it had been 
canceled or postponed 
the lithuanian legislature which began meeting in the late 
afternoon was scheduled to respond today to gorbachevs decree 
that the republic renounce its declaration of independence before 
any talks begin 
suggestions by some lithuanian communists that the small baltic 
nation suspend its declaration of independence for six months in 
hopes of appeasing gorbachev were adamantly opposed by members of 
the sajudis proindependence movement according to anatole lieven 
of the times of london one of the few correspondents not expelled 
from vilnius by soviet authorities 
lithuanian president vytautas landsbergis and the overwhelming 
majority of lithuanian citizens interviewed by the associated press 
over the past two weeks said soviet military intimidation had not 
ebbed their determination for independence 
if somebody expects lithuania to renounce its independence 
act there will be no such answer bickauskas said 
sajudis planned proindependence rallies in several lithuanian 
cities tonight but spokesman yuri romanenko said one scheduled for 
vilnius was canceled to prevent a clash with an antiindependence 
meeting set for the same spot in front of the parliament building 
90 minutes earlier 
as with earlier antiindependence demonstrations in the 
lithuanian capital publicity was handled by the soviet army which 
dropped announcements from a military helicopter on tuesday 
romanenko said 
gremitskikh also said today that soviet officials had never 
halted their dialogue with lithuanians and he specifically cited a 
visit to vilnius by several members of the national parliament 
the only such trip was taken by a group of democratically minded 
deputies who strongly supported lithuanias bid for independence 
and called on gorbachev to end his intransigence and start 
negotiating 
on tuesday the supreme soviet parliament approved a bill 
setting procedures for secession from the soviet union the soviet 
constitution allows republics to secede but until the legislation 
was passed there was no legal mechanism for beginning the procedure 
the law which becomes effective when it is published in the 
soviet press requires twothirds of a republics voters to approve 
secession in a referendum and calls for a subsequent waiting period 
of up to five years while the soviet union and the republic 
negotiate terms of secession 
bickauskas said lithuania had no means of implementing its 
proclaimed independence if soviet soldiers continued to interfere 
in the republic 
we have declared independence but we very well know that 
tanks are moving on our soil every day and night and they take 
over one building after another he said 
we realize the soviet union has economic political and 
military interests in lithuania that cannot be cut all at once 
these problems involve not only the soviet union and lithuania but 
europe and the whole world so we need to talk we want somebody to 
hold a dialogue with us bickauskas said 
on saturday gorbachev said secession talks could take place if 
lithuania renounced the independence declaration landsbergis 
responded monday that lithuania did not intend to rush toward 
freedom and invited a moscow representative for talks in vilnius 
