guards at graterford state prison have sued 
the state claiming they are endangered by overcrowding in the 
nations fifth largest prison 
the lawsuit filed tuesday in commonwealth court asks the court 
to order the state to reduce the prisons population to safer 
more manageable levels it also asks for improvements in the 
prisons sewage water and electrical facilities 
the lawsuit is believed to be the nations first by prison 
guards seeking to relieve prison crowding said michael fox 
assistant to the executive director of council 13 of the american 
federation of state county and municipal employees afscme is the 
union for state prison employees 
the department of corrections declined to comment until it sees 
the suit spokeswoman sherri cadeaux said 
the 61yearold 62acre maximumsecurity prison northwest of 
philadelphia has a capacity of 2734 inmates tuesday it held 
4212 inmates including 510 serving life sentences and 24 on death 
row prison spokesman alan j lefebvre said 
they are controlled by 506 corrections officers lefebvre said 
but 65 guard positions are unfilled because the state cant find 
anyone to work for the 17200 starting salary lefebvre said 
the concern is that the inmates could take over if they wanted 
to fox said 
we are hoping we can relieve it before it gets to that 
point lefebvre said he said the crowding causes long waiting 
lines for meals food shortages delays equipment breakdowns and a 
higher level of tension 
vince carocci spokesman for gov robert p casey who is named 
in the lawsuit said casey has proposed spending 180 million for 
