april 3 
winstonsalem nc journal on the idaho abortion bill 
abortion activists tossed gov cecil andrus of idaho a hot 
potato by threatening a boycott of the states most famous crop 
if he didnt veto a bill that would have given that state the 
nations most restrictive abortion law 
the governor a longtime abortion foe caved in he claimed 
the veto reflected his objection to the laws harsh provisions on 
rape cases and its unlikely prospects before the supreme court the 
risk of ruining his states economy must also have played a part 
however 
theres no question that abortion is both a wrenching moral 
issue and a legitimate subject for political debate but some of 
the tactics employed by zealots on either side of the issue 
threaten to go beyond free speech or even civil disobedience they 
threaten to undermine the democratic process 
in the last two presidential races candidates for the nations 
highest office have faced a constant barrage of heckling and 
disruption from abortion foes now that the webster decision has 
transferred much of the action to the state level political 
discourse is being held hostage in state races 
those involved in the issue argue that the fate of some crop is 
small potatoes alongside the lives of women or the deaths of the 
unborn but that misses the point 
no matter how important the abortion issue is to those caught up 
in it the tactic in idaho threatened to ruin the livelihoods if 
not the lives of potato farmers they were innocent bystanders who 
had no connection to the debate other than the accident of 
depending for their income on a product that could be turned into a 
convenient symbol 
a tactic that attempts to make a political point by ruining the 
lives and fortunes of victims selected more or less at random isnt 
democracy in action or noble protest its a species of terrorism 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 31 
the starledger newark nj on hungry children 
the eventful developments of recent months have made for banner 
headlines and historic change in the world the crumbling of 
communism in eastern europe the dismantling of the berlin wall 
the invasion of panama the elections in chile the coup attempt in 
the phillipines to name a few all have dominated the news 
and while the world has been watching scant attention is 
being paid to the needless deaths of tens of thousands of third 
world children each day from hunger and poverty 
the united nations international childrens emergency fund in 
its state of the worlds children1990 report notes that if 
current trends continue 100 million children will die in this 
decade from illness and malnutrition 
it also notes that these deaths could be prevented at low cost 
if the nations of the world have the will to address the problem a 
host of proposals that unicef says could save millions of lives a 
year would come with a 25 billion annual price tag the figure is 
equivalent to what soviets spend on vodka what american companies 
spend on cigarette advertisement in a year and 10 percent of the 
european communitys annual agriculture subsidy 
the unicef solutions should be seriously addressed the time is 
overdue for the developed nations of the world to demonstrate their 
commitment to ending the unnecessary deaths of children children 
who are dying to know if these nations have the will 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 30 
akron ohio beacon journal on the nuclear threat 
the threat of war between the united states and the soviet union 
has diminished but not the threat to world order from other 
sources 
a reminder of that came with the arrest in britain of six 
people who were trying to smuggle a triggering device for nuclear 
weapons into iraq 
this is the new world threat as tensions ease between the big 
powers the increasing spread of weapons of increasing 
destructiveness can mean that regional conflicts will be 
international concerns or that smaller terrorist nations can hold 
large powers hostage on their demands 
it is time to put tighter controls on the spread of nuclear 
weapons technology and to expand and enforce nuclear proliferation 
treaties 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
march 30 
beloit wis daily news on japan and the us economy 
according to a japanese newspaper a list of 80 suggestions to 
improve the united states economy has been delivered from tokyo to 
washington 
the japanese suggest the united states impose a valueadded tax 
abolish income tax deductions on home mortgage loans build 
highspeed trains to reduce the demand for automobiles and even 
limit the number of credit cards us citizens can possess 
the object is to cut the multibilliondollar us trade deficit 
with japan 
the united states isnt a basket case just yet and doesnt need 
lectures from the land of the rising sun 
the japanese flush with the economic success of recent years 
shouldnt forget just how dependent their industries are on the 
american marketplace presumptuous pronouncements of this type just 
feed an existing american resentment of japanese economic policies 
it also glosses over a key point in the trade deficit situation 
namely tokyos protectionist policies which thwart us companies 
efforts to compete in japan 
there may come a day when tokyo has the economic power to humble 
the united states and dictate fiscal policies but dont bet on it 
</TEXT>
