<TEXT>
the general medical council took disciplinary 
action wednesday against three doctors involved in a case in which 
four healthy people sold their kidneys for transplant operations 
the harshest action was taken against dr raymond crockett the 
council struck him from its register meaning he may not prescribe 
medicine until he is readmitted to the register he is eligible to 
reapply in 10 months 
the councils professional conduct committee found crockett and 
surgeons michael joyce and michael bewick guilty of serious 
professional misconduct but crockett was the only one struck off 
the register 
joyce and bewick were found to have failed to comply with 
guidelines on making checks on the histories of the patients and 
donors 
joyce was banned from taking part in kidney transplants for two 
years 
bewick was ordered to confine his services to the governments 
national health service for the next three years and to submit 
detailed records of every transplant operation in which he is 
involved 
they have 28 days to appeal 
this whole case has been about the limits to which it is 
permissible for a doctor to go to save lives thats all i have 
ever tried to do crockett said after the hearing my concern 
was with four of my patients who were going to die without an 
urgent transplant 
the committee chairman sir robert kilpatrick told crockett his 
conduct brought disgrace upon yourself and dishonor upon medical 
practice in the united kingdom 
during a 35day hearing the board heard allegations that 
crockett arranged for kidneys to be transplanted from four healthy 
turks into patients in london 
turkish authorities said the donors were paid 3200 to 5600 
ata nur kunter who has been identified as the broker in the 
transactions was not called to testify 
everybody knows if you have money you can buy a kidney 
