<TEXT>
negotiators for el salvador and the leftist rebels 
opened unmediated peace talks today and signed a declaration 
saying a truce in the nations 10yearold civil war is their 
initial objective 
the accord said the parties would try to end the armed 
conflict through political means as speedily as possible 
the declaration also said the negotiators hoped to promote moves 
toward democracy and respect for human rights in el salvador and 
toward integrating the guerrillas of the farabundo marti national 
liberation front into society 
the document also was signed by un secretarygeneral javier 
perez de cuellar who held brief separate meetings with the two 
sides today 
todays session the first peace talks on el salvador since 
october was the first time the united nations has sponsored such 
negotiations 
the civil war has killed 72000 people since 1980 
the two sides also agreed on the format for future talks 
they can either be facetoface negotiations mediated by perez 
de cuellar or his personal representative or involve un envoy 
bargaining separately with government and rebel delegations 
according to the accord 
the simple fact of agreeing on the procedure for the 
realization of the negotiating process is a considerable advance 
alvaro de soto perez de cuellars special envoy told reporters 
negotiators for el salvador and the rebels shook hands before 
signing the accord at todays public ceremony de soto later talked 
with the two sides to discuss procedures for the negotiations un 
officials said 
the parties then adjourned no date or location for the next 
session of talks was announced the teams were led by el salvadors 
justice minister oscar santamaria and rebel commander shafik 
handal 
de soto has been working to resume a dialogue between the 
government and the rebels since president alfredo cristiani of el 
salvador met with perez de cuellar in new york in february 
negotiations between the two sides were last held in october 
they were suspended after a union headquarters was bombed in 
november and the rebels opened an offensive in san salvador in 
which more than 1000 people died 
the agreement to resume peace talks came at a time of rising 
hopes for peace in central america 
chances for ending the el salvador conflict got a boost with the 
defeat five weeks ago of the leftwing sandinista government in 
nicaragua which has channeled weapons from cuba to the rebels 
according to us officials 
cristianis rightist government also has been hurt by falling 
prices for coffee a major export and a drop in us economic aid 
handal said the unsponsored dialogue must include issues such 
as restructuring the army and police judicial reforms and the 
reform of el salvadors electoral system 
we are optimistic now because these negotiations are in the 
framework of the united nations the rebel leader told a news 
conference this gives them a greater degree of seriousness and 
weight than in the past 
the salvadoran rebels in an open letter to this weeks summit 
of central american leaders in nicaragua proposed a plebiscite on 
constitutional reform to reduce the size of the countrys armed 
forces 
the proposed reform would also purge the military of rightwing 
elements and subject it to civilian authority 
the rebels urged that the plebiscite be held jointly with the 
1991 elections for a new national assembly in el salvador the 
letter said the rebels were willing to become peaceful political 
parties if an agreement was reached 
</TEXT>
