<TEXT>
logging must stop across a large section of 
national forests in the pacific northwest to keep the northern 
spotted owl from becoming extinct a government panel of scientists 
said wednesday 
environmentalists hailed the recommendations as an important 
step toward listing the owl as a threatened or endangered species 
but industry leaders said the panels proposals could devastate the 
regions timberbased economy 
the interagency committee led by us forest service biologist 
jack ward thomas recommended in a report a reduction of about 25 
percent in the allowable cut in national forests and a 30 percent 
to 40 percent reduction on bureau of land management areas 
we have concluded that the owl is imperiled over significant 
portions of its range because of continuing losses of habitat from 
logging and natural disturbances the report said current 
management strategies are inadequate to ensure its viability 
the panels recommendation is expected to weigh heavily in the 
us fish and wildlife services decision on whether to list the 
owl as a threatened or endangered species the service which must 
make a decision by june 23 extended its public comment period 
until april 11 to receive the panels recommendation 
make no mistake about it this is a very influential 
document said rep les aucoin dore heres the bluest of 
blueribbon committees yet put together and it has recommended a 
logging reduction they say thats the minimum necessary to 
sustain a population of owls 
the owl lives primarily in the neverlogged oldgrowth of 
western washington and oregon its population has been reduced by 
about 60 percent since 1800 the report said 
thomas said during a congressional hearing wednesday that if 
future federal harvests continued at current levels there would be 
a dramatic reduction in the owls population especially on 
washingtons olympic peninsula 
certainly we would see local extinction ultimately i think 
we would see overall extinction i dont know how long it would 
take he said 
thomas said there currently are about 1700 breeding pairs of 
owls in the northwest he said if the panels proposals are 
implemented the number could grow to 2200 pairs within 100 years 
if everything went right 
the study recommends current timber sales on federal lands 
continue as scheduled through the end of september the end of the 
fiscal year 
the report was delivered wednesday to a joint meeting of the 
agriculture subcommittee on forests family farms and energy the 
interior subcommittee on national parks and public lands and the 
merchant marine and fisheries subcommittee on fisheries and 
wildlife conservation 
f dale robertson chief of the forest service said his 
calculations indicated the recommendations would reduce timbersale 
programs on national forests with owls by 1 billion to 13 billion 
board feet that would be 30 percent to 40 percent below an 
alreadyreduced harvest level that resulted from a compromise 
worked out last year to ease the immediate threat to the spotted 
owl 
national forests gross revenues will decline resulting in a 
loss of payments to counties although these reductions may be 
offset with a rise in prices because of log shortages he said 
robertson said the recommendations would affect 27 million 
acres of the forest services commercial timber base including 
about 19 million acres in oregon and washington and about 800000 
acres in northern california 
robertson said thomas predicted more than 6 million acres would 
be affected overall but that many of those acres already are being 
protected 
cy jamison director of the bureau of land management said the 
total cut on blm lands in western oregon would drop about 335 
million board feet or between 30 percent and 40 percent if the 
proposals were adopted 
</TEXT>
