a private group said in a lawsuit filed 
wednesday that the pentagons biological warfare research program 
should be halted because potential environmental dangers havent 
been adequately examined 
the foundation on economic trends is seeking preliminary and 
permanent injunctions in us district court to terminate the 
program until the pentagon assesses possible harm from the research 
in greater depth 
an army analysis completed last year fails to analyze safety and 
security measures and emergency medical procedures at research 
sites around the country the lawsuit alleges 
the army study is grossly inadequate in assessing the 
nature of the severity of the impacts the research may have on 
human health and the environment said the lawsuit by the 
nonprofit group and its president jeremy rifkin 
laboratory research with biological materials is potentially 
hazardous concluded last years study but over the years 
elaborate controls have been developed to assure adequate 
protection for the environment 
the army said last year that the process of working with deadly 
toxins has actually become safer over the years 
better containment equipment and facilities became available 
and more effective biosafety protocols were developed 
the pentagons biological defense research program is conducted 
at more than 100 military university and private laboratories in 
27 states and eight foreign countries 
some 90 million was spent on the program in 1989 the lawsuit 
said last year the pentagon estimated the figure at 60 million 
annually 
chuck dasey public affairs officer for the us army medical 
research and development command at fort detrick md declined to 
comment saying he had not seen the lawsuit 
fort detrick is one of the biological research facilities 
