jurors in john m poindexters irancontra 
coverup trial deliberated a third day wednesday without a verdict 
on charges that the former national security adviser lied to 
lawmakers and obstructed congress 
the jury of eight women and four men sent no notes to us 
district judge harold greene that would indicate how the 
deliberations were proceeding 
poindexter 53 a retired navy rear admiral who was president 
reagans national security adviser from late 1985 until he resigned 
as the irancontra affair unraveled in november 1986 is accused of 
five felony counts of conspiracy obstructing congress and making 
false statements 
the indictment charges that poindexter falsely assured congress 
the national security council was not covertly assisting the 
nicaraguan contra rebels at a time when us military aid had been 
banned by congress 
poindexter is also accused of lying by stating that he did not 
learn of us involvement in a 1985 shipment of israeli hawk 
missiles to iran until two months after it occurred 
prosecutors argued that poindexter lied to conceal a politically 
embarrassing presidential finding signed by reagan that 
authorized the arms deal as part of an effort to trade weapons for 
american hostages 
the judge meanwhile denied a defense request to clarify an 
instruction he had given to the jury on tuesday when it asked to 
review more than 5000 copies of electronic messages stored in 
poindexters white house computer backup copies were found in the 
white house computer system 
the indictment charges that poindexter deleted the messages from 
his computer just days before he resigned 
greene told the jury it could not review them because the 
messages known as prof notes had not been admitted into evidence 
in a court filing poindexters lawyers urged greene to clarify 
this instruction saying it may mislead the jury into believing 
that it cannot base its decision upon other evidence about the 
notes 
the judge also denied the defense request that he tell the jury 
that the prof notes were not admitted into evidence because they 
contained classified information 
in a response prosecutor dan k webb said that greenes remarks 
tuesday were sufficient but that he did not object to further 
instructions out of an abundance of caution 
but the language webb proposed for the additional instruction 
contained no mention of the fact the notes were kept out of the 
case because they contained classified information 
the defense is trying to persuade jurors that poindexters 
actions was just a normal security precaution to protect classified 
documents 
in his closing argument last friday defense attorney richard 
beckler said poindexters deletions were the electronic 
equivalent of clearing out his desk 
prosecutors argued that at the time the files were deleted 
poindexter did not know that he would be resigning his job in the 
wake of the irancontra affair 
