court order in march 1986 to prohibit any further transactions 
involving the properties 
linn conceded that khashoggi had many personal dealings with the 
late marcos and that khashoggi had signed one fake document 
involving the buildings but said this was intended to help a 
marcos associate not to defraud anyone 
khashoggi once described as the richest man in the world was 
trying to head off moves by creditors to foreclose on the 
properties linn said 
marcos had offered khashoggi 10 percent of a shipload of gold if 
khashoggi could find a safe port for the vessel preferably in an 
arab country linn said marcos later told khashoggi he had made 
other arrangements for the gold he said 
prosecutors say khashoggi had been in contact with marcos to 
discuss faking documents to show that he not the marcoses had 
actually owned four manhattan buildings allegedly bought with more 
than 160 million stolen from the philippines treasury 
linn said khashoggi was innocent of the charges and had merely 
shown poor judgment in his dealings with the marcoses 
if this wasnt such a serious charge this would be funny 
he said it is not the sinister thing that the government makes 
it out to be 
linn said he would call a handwriting expert to testify that 
khashoggis initials were forged on other documents 
mrs marcos 60 has pleaded innocent to charges of 
racketeering racketeering conspiracy mail fraud and obstruction 
of justice if convicted she faces up to 50 years in prison and 1 
million in fines khashoggi faces up to 10 years in prison and 
500000 in fines if convicted 
the prosecutions first witness a former real estate broker 
with sothebys auction house testified about an art collection 
that marcoses allegedly bought with the embezzled funds 
thomas bryan of fairfax va said the collection of paintings 
furniture and antiques had been housed in the manhattan apartment 
of art collector leslie samuels who hired sothebys to sell both 
the cooperative apartment and its contents after his wife passed 
away 
under questioning by assistant us attorney charles labella 
bryan said mrs marcos first saw the collection in 1981 on a tour 
of the apartment with gliceria tantoco a marcos associate who 
owned a philippine department store 
mrs tantoco and her husband who had been the philippine 
ambassador to the vatican fled after being charged with the 
marcoses 
samuels personally showed them around the apartment and later 
invited them to dinner at his new residence at the waldorf towers 
where mrs marcos also was staying bryan testified 
later that evening after the party had moved to mrs marcos 
rooms for entertainment bryan said mrs tantoco approached him and 
said we are very interested in purchasing the contents and the 
apartment itself 
they negotiated a deal with samuels and agreed on a tentative 
price of 8 million for the apartment and just under 6 million for 
the art collection he said 
at a later meeting bryan said he told mrs tantoco and mrs 
marcos that the apartment could not be bought by a corporation but 
only by an individual who was to be the principal user after the 
two women held a brief discussion he said mrs tantoco asked if he 
would be willing to put his name on the contract 
i said it was not possible due to my current financial 
situation and salary and because the board would have a hard time 
understanding how i came up with the money bryan said prompting 
laughter he said his salary at the time was 27000 a year 
bryan said the art collection was purchased by a corporation 
but the apartment fell through because mrs tantoco was rejected as 
a buyer by the cooperatives board 
when he expressed his regret to mrs marcos about the boards 
denial bryan testified she told him she had purchased another 
piece of real estate that day the genesco building that 
building now called the crown building is one of the four 
properties named in the indictment 
</TEXT>
