<TEXT>
west german foreign minister hansdietrich 
genscher said wednesday that the soviet union eventually may agree 
that a unified germany should be in nato 
genscher said at a news conference after meeting with president 
bush that he expected international agreement would be completed on 
german unification this year and that the first elections in a 
unified state could take place next year 
he said he expected the soviets would raise their opposition to 
unified germanys membership in the north atlantic treaty 
organization when east and west germany meet with the four major 
world war ii victors in coming weeks 
but genscher said it is my belief that the opinions in the 
soviet union about nato membership have not been finalized and 
that the soviets could be persuaded that it will serve their 
security interests to have a unified germany in nato 
the western allies are convinced it will make europe more stable 
to have germany in nato and that a neutral germany would create 
uncertainty and lead to instability he said 
also countries like poland czechoslovakia and hungary will 
have an influence on the forming of the soviet opinion in this 
respect he said the soviet union will see how this can 
preserve their own security 
genscher said the two german governments were determined that 
unity would threaten no other country and that the legitimate 
security interest of the soviet union will be taken into 
consideration to the fullest 
he reiterated his support for developing a security framework 
for all of europe the united states and canada by working through 
the process built on the 1975 helsinki accords of 35 nations 
pledging themselves to security and cooperation in europe 
but genscher said the german support for such a framework did 
not undermine germanys commitment to nato 
the western alliance will not be in any way abandoned he 
said there is no doubt that the alliance will last a long time 
genscher said the europe economic community also would play a 
major role in fostering stability for the region 
we are more and more convinced that the european community 
will become more and more an anchor of stability in europe he 
said adding that poland czechoslovakia hungary bulgaria 
romania and even the soviet union want the closest possible ties to 
the community and that some even want to become members 
bonn and washington are in complete agreement on all the 
basic issues he said 
one area of difference between the two governments has been over 
us insistence that west germanbased shortrange lance nuclear 
missiles be modernized the west germans say the weapons are 
pointless because they can only hit eastern europe which no longer 
poses a threat to the west 
genscher said the lance didnt come up in his talks 
genscher asked whether soviet reaction to moves for 
independence by lithuania would affect german unification said 
we hope that through responsible actions of all parties involved 
we will get a responsible solution 
