<TEXT>
the doctor treating lee atwater for a brain 
tumor said wednesday the growth is aggressive and dangerous 
and will require chemotherapy in addition to radiation treatment 
in a statement issued through the republican party headquarters 
dr paul l kornblith said that working in atwaters favor were the 
facts that he was in excellent health and the lesion is quite 
small and has been detected early in its development 
atwater was in montefiore medical center in new york city where 
a team of physicians led by kornblith implanted radioactive 
isotopes into the tumor tuesday in an effort to kill the growth on 
the right frontal lobe of atwaters brain 
the procedure took approximately four hours and was 
uneventful said kornblith he added that it was completed 
without apparent impairment to any neurological functions 
although it is obvious that this tumor is aggressive and 
dangerous mr atwater has many factors working in his favor 
kornblith said 
a party official said the 39yearold atwater was receiving 
numerous visitors in a new york hospital wednesday though they had 
to stand behind a lead shield because of radioactivity 
party chief of staff mary matalin said the radioactive device 
would be removed on friday and that recuperation was expected to 
take several weeks 
atwaters wife sally who is expecting to deliver the couples 
third child on monday was in new york with him 
kornblith said the growth known as a astrocytoma was the most 
common primary brain tumor 
it does not spread to other parts of the body but can cause 
damage to brain tissue by pressure and by invasion the doctor 
said 
a brain tumor undergoing unrestrained growth would cause 
pressure within the closed skull this pressure would kill normal 
brain cells thus bringing eventual death by destroying vital 
functions 
brain tumors can also spread by extension into other parts of 
the central nervous system and displace normal cells during such a 
process there would be a progressive loss of function as normal 
brain cells associated with memory thought muscle control and 
even heart beat and respiration are lost 
kornblith said that in order to assure that any tumor cells 
peripheral to the main lesion are destroyed he will be receiving 
chemotherapy as well 
this particular form of chemotherapy is given orally once 
every six weeks and will not limit his activities or functions 
the doctor said atwater will be able to be discharged from the 
hospital in a few days and may well be able to return to work in 
some degree within a couple of weeks 
he will need to be followed closely and may need to have 
additional therapies in the future for the present we are 
delighted with his progress 
</TEXT>
