<TEXT>
a bill introduced in congress on wednesday 
would give the bush administration an opportunity to remove aids 
from a list of contagious diseases used to prevent foreigners from 
entering the united states 
the bill was sponsored by rep j roy rowland dga on behalf 
of the national commission on aids the administrations position 
on the bill was not clear 
the federal centers for disease control recently recommended 
that aids be stricken from the list along with several other 
diseases that recommendation is under review by the department of 
health and human services but officials say the department lacks 
authority to remove it 
the bill would give hhs explicit authority over the list 
sponsors said 
the entry restrictions have prompted dozens of international 
organizations and agencies to call for a boycott of the sixth 
international conference on aids in san francisco in june france 
and switzerland also have said they wont send official delegations 
to the meeting 
it seems such a compelling thing said dr june osborn 
chairwoman of the national commission on aids whose members were 
appointed by congress and the white house 
the us is being looked at with such astonishing horror by 
officials and organizations in other countries she said 
under a law passed in 1987 by congress infection with the human 
immunodeficiency virus or hiv which causes aids was added to the 
list of contagious diseases for which foreigners can be barred from 
entering the country 
administration officials have said they do not have the 
authority to eliminate the restriction and have done all they can 
within the limits of their power including expediting waivers for 
those who want to attend the conference but they have said that 
since congress directed that aids be put on the list congressional 
action would be required to remove it 
rep henry waxman dcalif one of the cosponsors of the bill 
said that while he believes the administration already has the 
authority to act the legislation would make that authority 
absolutely clear 
the measure would give the hhs secretary authority to decide 
which diseases pose a threat to the public health and would require 
exclusion from the country it does not mention hiv or aids 
we should let health officials make the health decisions 
waxman said that is what we did before 1987 and that is what we 
should continue to do 
