<TEXT>
one of space shuttle atlantis fuel 
cells probably was damaged because excessive pressure was exerted 
when the unit was being prepared for removal nasa said wednesday 
the extent of damage was not immediately known said dick young 
a spokesman for the national aeronautics and space administration 
there are enough other fuel cells in the system for flight and 
any damage will not affect atlantis next mission in july atlantis 
returned to kennedy space center on march 13 following a secret 
pentagon mission to send a 500 million spy satellite into orbit 
fuel cells provide electrical power to space shuttles through a 
reaction between liquid hydrogen and liquid oxygen 
one of the fuel cell units 96 individual cells had failed a 
voltage test during a postflight checkout march 31 young said 
nasa decided to remove the entire unit and return it for repair 
to the vendor international fuel cells of hartford conn young 
said the unit had been purged with gaseous helium following the 
march 31 test and residual gas pressure was being vented out 
wednesday 
as the operation proceeded it became apparent that the oxygen 
vent was working but the hydrogen vent was not nasa said in a 
statement issued wednesday night it was discovered that a cap 
had been placed on the vehicles hydrogen vent port possibly as a 
conclusion of the march 31 electrical test 
the procedure was halted immediately and the area was cleared 
of workers as a safety precaution young said 
the oxygen and hydrogen sides of the fuel cells are divided by a 
plate an eighth of an inch thick containing potassium hydroxide a 
corrosive chemical used as an electrolyte pressure normally is 
kept higher on the oxygen side of the cell to keep the potassium 
hydroxide from seeping through 
young said the potassium hydroxide likely was forced into the 
oxygen side of the cell causing the difference in pressure on 
either side to exceed allowable levels that could affect the fuel 
cells operation and corrode the oxygen piping he said 
the fuel cell will be removed as soon as possible young said 
young said nasa planned to appoint a review board to investigate 
the matter he declined to comment further 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

