<TEXT>
key members of the house energy and commerce 
committee negotiated behind closed doors late wednesday in an 
attempt to craft a compromise on the acid rain provision of a clean 
air bill 
a day after the senate approved a sweeping air pollution control 
bill of its own the focus of the debated shifted to the house 
where the committee is trying to work out final details of similar 
legislation 
rep john dingell dmich the panels chairman said he hopes 
remaining issues can be settled this week and a final committee 
vote taken that might lead to house floor action on the bill early 
next month 
rep philip sharp dind floated a revised proposal aimed at 
helping midwest utilities cope with tough new acid rain pollution 
controls the proposal involved a complex system of pollution 
allowances and was similar to a provision already in the senate 
bill according to committee sources 
but as of 10 pm edt the measure was still being discussed and 
sources said it was unlikely a final agreement could be reached 
before thursday 
the senate voted 8911 late tuesday in favor of a sweeping clean 
air bill that imposes new emission controls on automobiles 
factories and electric power plants the bill was a product of a 
compromise agreement between senate leaders and the white house 
president bush at a white house meeting congratulated senate 
leaders for helping us at last break the legislative logjam on 
clean air but called it only a first step 
more progress is going to be needed if were to achieve the 
balanced bill that is essential bush said he said the white 
house would keep pushing in the house and in the eventual 
conference committee for changes to ensure cleaner air without 
major job loss 
neither industry nor environmentalists have been happy about the 
senate legislation with environmental groups calling it inadequate 
to solve urban smog problems and industry charging its toxic 
chemical controls and acid rain provisions are too expensive 
senate majority leader george mitchell meeting with reporters 
on wednesday said he would have preferred that it were stronger in 
some areas including tougher secondround controls on automobile 
emissions 
but mitchell called the bill strong and comprehensive 
mitchell said he knew early on that he did not have enough votes to 
stop a filibuster on the original senate bill and concluded the 
only way to enact the legislation was to work out a compromise with 
the bush administration 
we did what was necessary to pass the bill said mitchell 
mitchell indicated that he intended to push for some 
improvements he favored when the bill goes to a conference 
committee to be reconciled with the eventual house legislation 
much of the fight in the house however was expected to revolve 
around the strong acid rain control measures included in both the 
house and senate legislation 
both bills call for a 10 million ton reduction in the annual 
releases of sulfur dioxide from coalfired electric power plants 
the curbs will hit midwest utilities especially hard because they 
rely heavily on highsulfur coal and have some of the dirtiest 
plants 
a group of congressmen led by rep philip sharp dind has 
sought to include in the house bill a cost sharing measure to 
ease the financial burden of cleaning up the midwest plants 
the senate provided some help by allowing midwest states special 
pollution allowances that could be sold to other utilities but 
generally rejected as has the white house further costsharing 
ideas 
dingell has proposed some costsharing options and sharp was 
continuing to pursue a proposal calling for a fee on industrial 
polluters of sulfur dioxide which are not covered by the acid rain 
provision to offset the costs to utilities 
if the acid rain issues can be resolved there appears little 
impediment on getting the bill out of committee before congress 
goes on its easter recess at the end of the week a congressional 
source suggested dingell said he hoped for a final vote thursday 
or friday 
