<TEXT>
the news from the nations capital was 
somewhat encouraging fewer people taken into police custody 
tested positive for cocaine but around the country law 
enforcement officials say they see no sign that drug abuse and 
trafficking are abating 
the situation is bleak in that cocaine is still readily 
available in the united states despite very significant and very 
effective law enforcement initiatives both domestically and in 
latin america said frank shults a spokesman for the drug 
enforcement agency 
a dea survey last september and october revealed that the price 
of cocaine at the kilogram level has increased slightly moving 
from 13000 to 14000 in los angeles he said 
unfortunately he said this doesnt mean theres a cocaine 
shortage 
we attribute it to price gouging at low and midlevel 
trafficking and individuals who are taking advantage of the users 
fear of a shortage shults said 
he said the fear stems from some significant law enforcement 
advances 
the colombian governments crackdown on drug trafficking has 
disrupted operations of the medellin cartel 
the price of coca leaf paid to farmers in bolivia and peru has 
dropped to 5 to 10 per hundred pounds far below the growers 
breakeven point of 30 per hundred pounds the price drop occurred 
because of the colombian crackdown an oversupply of leaf more 
efficient processing techniques and better controls of chemicals 
used to make cocaine he said 
the seizure of 20 tons of cocaine at one los angeles warehouse 
in the fall combined with several other major busts around the 
country 
nevertheless the purity of cocaine at the kilo level has 
remained high approximately 84 percent throughout the united 
