<TEXT>
a shareholder upset by the last temptation 
of christ is urging other holders of mca inc stock to tell the 
company not to make films that might offend religious groups 
the proposal was included in proxy materials sent to 
shareholders this week ahead of a vote at the companys annual 
meeting may 8 in chicago 
a supporting statement for the proposal says last temptation 
showed jesus as a disturbed man who frequents brothels 
hallucinates seeing snakes vows that he always tells lies acts 
only as a result of fearand feels tormented by god 
the proposal made by stockholder dean shahinian of alexandria 
va calls for shareholders to censure mca for antichristian 
effects 
we urge management to establish a corporate policy not to use 
corporate assets to falsely defame jesus christ or other major 
religious leaders it says 
mca urged shareholders to reject the proposal saying that 
censoring a film because it contains an unconventional religious 
viewpoint could stifle religious and creative expression 
noting that martin scorsese won a best director oscar nomination 
for temptation mca said the film was scorseses interpretation 
of a novel not the companys view of christ 
the proxy materials also disclosed that mcas top executives 
were awarded hefty compensation last year 
film chief thomas pollock was given mca stock worth 57 million 
in 1989 and stock options worth 78 million when issued last 
august 
pollock also was paid a base salary of 627000 bringing his 
total compensation to more than 14 million his salary was raised 
to 850000 this year 
sidney sheinberg president of the universal citybasedmovie 
tv music and theme park giant was issued stock worth 72 million 
last year his salary jumps from 729000 in 1989 to 900000 mca 
chairman lew wassermans salary also jumps to 900000 from 
559000 
the shareholders will vote on a new stock option plan under 
which pollock was given his options 
the plan authorizes the issuance of 5 million new shares 
600000 of which would become available to pollock at 55 a share 
over the next five years he may exercise 20 percent of the options 
once per year beginning this july 
mcas stock was trading at 68 a share when they were awarded 
last august it has since fallen in value closing at 5050 on the 
new york stock exchange tuesday at that level pollock would lose 
money by exercising his options 
mcas last stock option plan was approved in 1968 but never 
exercised the company said the new plan was needed to provide 
competitive compensation for mca executives 
that was a reference to corporations like the walt disney co 
whose chairman president frank wells made 724 million on the sale 
of stock bought through options in 1989 
</TEXT>
