<DOCNO> AP900404-0198 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
general development corp mired in legal and 
financial problems is closing its global network of homesite 
sales offices 
general development announced tuesday it was shutting 24 offices 
in this country as well as bureaus in europe canada and the far 
east and laying off about 1100 workers 
the company is trying to stay out of bankruptcy court and 
recover from a scandal involving a scheme to sell overpriced homes 
thomas d wood a coral gablesbased mortgage banker and 
attorney was named tuesday to examine general developments 
agreement to reimburse nearly 10000 victims of the overpricing 
scheme the agreement was part of a settlement of federal fraud 
charges against the firm 
us district court judge lenore nesbitt said woods role was to 
make the restitution pact acceptable workable and realistic 
general development said the closure of its offices would not 
affect the restitution plan 
the cost of generating sales in these offices no longer makes 
economic sense said company president charles simons also 
given the parameters of the proposed consent decree we are not 
confident that those guidelines are being met on a daily basis in 
many of our offices 
the company will continue to sell existing homes at its nine 
florida communities the focus of the us attorneys office 
twoyear probe into pricing practices 
a federal indictment accused the company and two former 
executives of an elaborate scheme to sell homes with highly 
inflated prices compared with similar florida dwellings the 
victims many from the northeast and midwest were deceived into 
purchasing homes an average of 40 percent higher than market value 
prosecutors said 
a week after the march 16 indictment attorneys for general 
development entered a guilty plea to one fraud count that could 
bring a maximum 500000 fine 
at the same hearing general developments former president 
robert ehrling and former chairman david brown also pleaded guilty 
to one fraud count each faces a maximum of five years in prison a 
250000 fine and some restitution payments sentencing is 
scheduled for may 22 
the plan which still needs final court approval covers general 
development homebuyers from jan 1 1983 to jan 1 1989 and 
establishes a complicated formula to determine how much money will 
be returned 
a courtappointed master will set the restitution amount by 
determining the difference between each homes net price and 
appraised value 
in cases of cash purchases for example the difference would be 
paid in installments over 25 years for those with a mortgage 
through the companys financial division the company would offset 
a portion of the monthly payment 
under the plan general development would pay restitution up to 
25 million a year for the first five years and a smaller portion 
later it would also be required to put up collateral valued at 
125 million by july 1 
discussions of restitution are complicated by cash shortages at 
general development which announced monday that negotiations for 
60 million in shortterm credit fell apart and it might seek 
chapter 11 bankruptcy protection 
assistant us attorney norman moscowitz and company spokesman 
otis wragg iii declined to comment on how a bankruptcy filing would 
affect the restitution program 
meanwhile general development is the target of several 
burgeoning classaction suits stemming from the overpricing scheme 
and conditions in the florida communities in delaware a major 
shareholder has filed suit seeking to oust six company directors 
</TEXT>
