<DOCNO> AP900404-0201 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the house has approved antitakeover 
legislation considered the toughest in the nation meant to make it 
more difficult for corporate raiders to grab or threaten 
pennsylvania companies 
the 18210 vote tuesday sends the bill back to the senate where 
members must consider amendments added by the house several 
senators and aides predicted the bill backed by gov robert p 
casey would gain easy passage on its second trip through the upper 
chamber 
if enacted corporate takeover strategists would be denied 
shortterm profits from takeover attempts the provision would 
apply when a takeover artist tries to sell holdings within 18 
months of a failed buyout bid 
the bill also would deny raiders immediate voting rights and 
would require management to consider employee and community 
interests along with stockholder concerns in deciding takeover 
offers 
democratic representative fred taylor a supporter of the 
measure said it would protect pennsylvania jobs companies and 
communities 
were sending a message with this bill to corporate raiders 
who have gone into pennsylvania laid waste to companies and forced 
them to buy back their own stock practically bankrupting them 
taylor said 
were telling them pennsylvania is not the playground of wall 
street this doesnt outlaw takeovers all together but it is 
certainly going to make that proposition a lot more difficult to 
participate in he said 
opponents have said the measure would stifle investment in 
pennsylvania the chairman of the securities and exchange 
commission criticized the pennsylvania bill monday saying it would 
disenfranchise shareholders and leave incompetent managers free 
to run a company into the ground 
republican representative robert godshall who oppposed the 
bill said it would take away fundamental and basic rights of 
shareholders i dont think this is good for pennsylvania labor i 
dont think its good for pennsylvania industry and i dont think 
its good for the state of pennsylvania 
the house made some minor changes to the bill but the its 
sponsor republican senator noah wenger said it appeared largely 
intact wenger said he expected the senate to reconsider the bill 
in about two weeks the senate initially passed the bill in 
december 454 
in the long run it will strengthen not only employment 
oportunities but investment opportunites those people who make 
the big bucks in takeovers would naturally be opposed to those 
things wenger said 
the measure stems from an effort to help a prominent 
pennsylvania company armstrong world industries fight off a 
hostile takeover attempt by the belzberg family of canada belzberg 
holds more than 10 percent of the company stock and is seeking to 
put its candidate on the board of directors 
william a k titelman a harrisburg lobbyist who represents the 
belzbergs said the legislation was a form of corporate 
stalinism 
the effect of this bill can be summed up in one sentence 
regardless of competence or performance the top management of a 
publicly owned corporation shall not be changed except with their 
express consent and regardless of the wishes of the owners of the 
corporation he said 
more than half the states have enacted takeover laws but only 
indiana has a section similar to pennsylvanias proposal to 
diminish directors financial responsibility to stockholders 
under the legislation company managers would be able to decide 
to exempt their companies from the proposed law within 90 days of 
its enactment workers laid off 90 days prior to the completion of 
a takeover would be eligible for a lump sum severance of one weeks 
pay for each year of service up to 26 weeks 
</TEXT>
