<TEXT>
complex trade negotiations with japan entered 
an unscheduled third day today as us trade ambassador carla hills 
warned that the japanese must make concessions or face growing 
prospects of economic retaliation by the united states 
the negotiations aimed at making broad structural reforms in 
the economies of both the united states and japan began monday 
with the arrival of a 64member delegation from japan 
while both sides are insisting that progress is being made the 
talks had originally been scheduled to conclude on tuesday 
however negotiators met for a third day of closeddoor bargaining 
at the state department talks on both monday and tuesday went late 
into the night 
hills denied that the lengthy negotiations indicated unexpected 
roadblocks had developed 
there is no deadlock we are making progress she told 
reporters following a speech to the national association of 
manufacturing we want to get it done 
hills told officials of the big industry lobbying group that the 
marketopening moves being proposed by the american side were in 
the selfinterest of japanese consumers who currently pay the 
highest prices in the industrial world for many products 
as she has done in the past she said that without trade 
concessions on the part of the japanese to correct the huge 
usjapan trade imbalance there would be growing pressure in this 
country to retaliate by raising the cost of japanese products 
if the japanese do not open up the second largest market in 
the world there will be enormous political pressure she told 
the manufacturing officials 
president bush was scheduled to meet today with former 
ambassador to washington nobuo matsunaga who was dispatched to 
washington as the personal emissary of japanese prime minister 
toshiki who has made resolution of usjapan trade frictions a 
top priority of his government 
presidential spokesman marlin fitzwater said that we seem to 
have made good progress on trade disputes involving 
supercomputers and satellites in the twoandahalf days of talks 
with japan 
we still have differences we still have some difficult issues 
to resolve but at least we feel that a good starts been made 
fitzwater said 
after months of no progress with japan on trade there have been 
three agreements reached in the past 10 days on opening japanese 
markets for sale of americanmade telecommunications products 
supercomputers and satellites the satellite agreement was 
announced late tuesday 
even with the flurry of new agreements american business 
leaders urged caution noting that the japanese over the past 
decade have prepared a variety of trade packages which have not 
produced the promised results americas deficit with japan totaled 
49 billion last year close to half of the total 109 billion 
trade imbalance 
i still think it is up in the air whether the trade talks will 
yield any meaningful results said jerry jasinowski president of 
the national association of manufacturers which was to receive a 
progress report today on trade negotiations from us trade 
representative carla hills 
the bush administration last july launched discussions with 
japan aimed at removing broad structural barriers in both the 
united states and japan that were viewed as primary reasons for the 
trade imbalance 
under the format for the talks known as the structural 
impediments initiative both sides have presented their own list of 
the economic failings they would like to see corrected in the other 
country 
the united states has pushed for changes in japan that would 
expand opportunities for us and other foreign firms to provide 
products and services arguing that such proposals were in the 
selfinterest of the japanese because they would lower consumer 
costs 
japan has targeted various us failings that hurt americas 
ability to compete internationally the japanese would like to see 
more done by us officials to lower the budget deficit improve 
the educational system and get us businesses to focus on 
longterm goals rather than quick profits 
negotiators hope to have an interim progress report completed by 
midapril with a final report on structural barriers finished in 
july 
