<TEXT>
ford motor co is paying 6 million to settle a 
suit that stemmed from the automakers failure to offer rear 
shoulder harness restraints for the trafficaccident death of a 
child and crippling injuries to his twin 
the settlement announced wednesday is the largest paid in a case 
involving the lack of rear shoulder harnesses said san diego 
attorney craig mcclellan he negotiated the settlement on behalf of 
the twins parents jim and patricia miller who also survived the 
nov 13 1988 accident 
this landmark settlement clearly demonstrates that 
manufacturers will be responsible for failing to install the 
shoulder restraints in pre1990 models said mcclellan dozens of 
similar suits filed throughout the nation are pending against ford 
and other automakers 
under federal regulations combination lap and shoulder safety 
harnesses in the rear are mandatory for all passenger cars as of 
this model year in 1992 the requirement will be expanded to 
include minivans 
ford admitted no liability in the settlement negotiated over 
the past two weeks before a superior court judge approved it 
the millers car a 1986 ford escort was equipped with lap 
belts only in the rear which both boys were wearing on the day of 
the accident 
reliable government studies show that lap belts in rear 
seating positions which have been installed on 140 million cars 
both ford and nonfords are effective in reducing the risk of 
death and serious injury in a collision ford spokesman mark 
miller said from detroit he is not related to the victims family 
certainly this is a tragic situation and ford sympathizes with 
the miller family at the same time ford was not responsible for 
the accident i think experts would agree it would be very 
unfortunate if people stopped using rear lap belts because they can 
enhance safety and reduce the risk of injury and fatality mark 
miller added 
the suit stemmed from a head oncollision on a notorious s 
curve on rancho santa fe road in carlsbad about 40 miles north of 
san diego in which a another car crossed into the wrong lane and 
crashed into the millers car the other driver also died 
on tuesday night the carlsbad city council approved a 550000 
payment to the millers to settle their claims the city also has 
realigned the curve to make the roadway safer 
the front end of the escort was nearly demolished in the 
accident but james and patricia miller survived with broken bones 
and bruises they were strapped in their front seats with shoulder 
harnesses 
mcclellan said the escorts rear compartment was left virtually 
intact but 11yearold james miller died in the crash and his twin 
brother richard suffered a fractured spine when he was pitched 
forward violently both of the boys were wearing their lap belts 
there is no question mcclellan said that james miller would 
have survived and richard miller would not have become a paraplegic 
if they had been wearing shoulder harnesses 
jim miller said had he been given an option he would have paid 
to have rear shoulder harnesses in his escort 
our experience clearly shows that anyone riding or driving in 
a car without rear shoulder harnesses should be concerned about the 
risk they are taking every time they go for a drive even buckled 
up jim miller said 
mcclellan estimated the additional cost at 12 per belt he also 
noted that ford has been installing rear shoulder restraints in 
escorts sold in europe since the early 1980s 
ford never offered the us market the rearset shoulder 
harness mandated by law in european escorts because of the expense 
12 per belt mcclellan said the miller family tragedy is a 
result of that conduct 
the attorney said fords own engineers told management years ago 
that a shoulder restraint system was more effective than lap belts 
in reducing the risk of injury or death in a collision and that any 
argument against their installation was outweighed by increased 
safety benefits 
</TEXT>
