<TEXT>
occidental petroleum corp is justified 
in funding a museum to house the art collection of chairman armand 
hammer because it enhances occidentals image a lawyer for a 
shareholder group said wednesday 
the oil and chemical business is risky attorney william 
prickett said at a hearing before maurice hartnett vice chancellor 
of the delaware chancery court 
prickett cited the love canal toxic waste incident and an 
explosion that killed 167 workers on a north sea oil platform as 
examples of tragedies that have hurt occidentals reputation given 
those risks building a museum to house a prominent collection is a 
legitimate public relations expense for the company he maintained 
this is a unique chance for occidental to be favorably 
identified in the public eye he said 
prickett was defending a settlement the shareholder group has 
reached with occidental that allows the company to continue to fund 
the museum within certain limits 
the court proceeding was called to hear a challenge to the 
settlement by other shareholders who have filed two separate 
classaction lawsuits seeking to stop the company from spending 
money on the museum attorneys for these shareholders contended the 
museums main purpose is to enhance the reputation of occidentals 
91yearold chief 
the museum is a gift to armand hammer that raised more 
controversy and ill will than good will said californias deputy 
attorney general susan henrichsen representing the california 
public employees retirement system 
calpers the nations largest pension fund owns 06 percent of 
occidentals stock 
occidental has said it will cost about 95 million to build the 
museum and establish an endowment to sustain it construction 
already has begun on a site next to the companys headquarters in 
the westwood district of los angeles 
hartnett listened to both sides but did not rule and gave no 
indication when he would do so occidental is based in los angeles 
but incorporated in delaware 
pricketts shareholder group originally filed a lawsuit 
challenging the museum the group dropped its suit after reaching a 
settlement with the oil company that would limit its spending on 
the project and require occidentals name to appear on the museum 
as well as hammers the settlement also included a fee of 14 
million for prickett 
hartnett earlier called the proposed 14 million payment 
huge and prickett said he would not dispute the matter if the 
judge lowered the award 
the occidental chairman announced plans to build the armand 
hammer museum of art and cultural center after reneging on a 
promise to give his 400 million collection to the los angeles 
county museum of art he and the county museum had been embroiled 
in a dispute about how the art would be displayed 
prickett contended that a special committee of occidentals 
independent directors was justified in approving corporate funding 
for the museum he noted that delaware courts have been hesitant to 
intervene in cases involving business judgments made after 
reasonable consideration such as the timewarner merger 
grover brown a lawyer for the special committee defended the 
panels support for the project and said committee members had a 
combined 80 years experience in deciding what was best for 
occidental 
the egocentrism of dr hammer is not a matter for the court 
brown said 
</TEXT>
