<TEXT>
investor marvin davis has no intention of 
making a new bid for ual corp despite the companys invitation to 
do so sources close to the negotiations said wednesday 
the beverly hills billionaire bid 275 a share for the parent of 
united airlines last august about 62 billion he was topped by a 
300ashare offer for the chicagobased company by team that 
included ual management pilots and british airways 
that deal fell through last october for lack of financing 
however causing uals share price to plummet 
uniteds pilots mechanics and flight attendants unions recently 
have made a new bid estimated to be worth about 185 a share in 
cash debt and stock 
union spokesmen said they never believed davis would make a new 
offer even though ual last month called off a standstill agreement 
with davis freeing him to bid again for the company 
the ual move was seen as an attempt to avert a proxy war by the 
companys largest shareholder coniston partners coniston which 
owns 118 percent of uals shares supported the unions bid and 
said it would wage a proxy battle to take over the board of 
directors if the offer was not accepted 
crains chicago business reported this week that davis had 
suggested a concept to the ual board for a bid of about 220 a 
share the range the board has indicated would be acceptable 
but two sources with knowledge of the situation who spoke on 
condition of anonymity said wednesday that davis would not renew 
his bid for ual 
one source said the unions had made clear they would strike if 
davis or another investor challenged their bid 
no bank will lend into the face of a strike he said 
youve got the union trying to blackmail the board and they have 
the ability to keep anybody else from playing 
he added that the unions will have problems arranging financing 
themselves even at the lower bid level since no one outside has 
offered to help them 
theres no equity partner there so the banks arent willing 
to finance the deal he said 
